         <abstract>
            <p>The problem addressed is this: Do there exist nonconsecutive integers $n_0, n_1, n_2,\ldots,$ such that the second differences of the squares of the $n_i$ are constant? Specifically, can that constant be equal to 2? A complete characterization of sequences of length four can be given. The question of whether or not sequences of length five exist is still open but the existence or nonexistence of such sequences can be described in a more algorithmic way than the simple statement of the problem.</p>
          </abstract>
